\begin_layout Exercise
In this exercise,
 you will study a new function called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the Error Function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\erf$
\end_inset

 for short.
 This function is defined by the expression
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\erf(x)=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\int_{0}^{x}\e^{-t^{2}}\,\dl t.
\]

\end_inset

This function appears very frequently in all branches of science,
 especially those that interface with statistics.
 Its significance stems from the fact that,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the outcome of a random process that is affected by many independent factors,
 the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is less than some value 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is very closely related to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\erf$
\end_inset

 function.
 More precisely,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has mean 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

,
 the following equation is true:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}(X\leq x)=\erf(x)$
\end_inset

.
 This is all related to something called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the central limit theorem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

