\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\diffx\erf(x)=\diffx\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\int_{0}^{x}\e^{-t^{2}}\,\dl t=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\diffx\int_{0}^{x}\e^{-t^{2}}\,\dl t=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\e^{-x^{2}}$
\end_inset

,
 where the last step used the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\erf(0)=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\int_{0}^{0}\e^{-t^{2}}\,\dl t=0$
\end_inset

,
 because an integral that starts and ends in the same place is always zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We saw that the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\erf(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\e^{-x^{2}}$
\end_inset

,
 which is always a product of positive numbers and hence positive.
 Therefore,
 since the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\erf(x)$
\end_inset

 is always positive,
 it must be an increasing function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\erf(x)$
\end_inset

 is differentiable everywhere (we calculated its derivative as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\e^{-x^{2}}$
\end_inset

),
 it must be continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{x\to+\infty}\erf(x)$
\end_inset

 is,
 as we saw in the previous homework,
 the same as the improper integral
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{x\to\infty}\erf(x)=\lim_{x\to\infty}\int_{0}^{x}\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\e^{-t^{2}}\,\dl t=\int_{0}^{\infty}\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\e^{-t^{2}}\,\dl t=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\int_{0}^{\infty}\e^{-t^{2}}\,\dl t.
\]

\end_inset

The improper integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\infty}\e^{-t^{2}}\,\dl t$
\end_inset

 represents the shaded area in Figure 
