 because as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to\infty$
\end_inset

 the value is increasing to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 (from below),
 but never reaching it or any number above it;
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to-\infty$
\end_inset

 the value is decreasing to 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 (from above) but never reaching it or any number below it,
 and since the function is continuous,
 it reaches all numbers in between.
\end_layout

